article.headline: Nevada 76, San Jose State 61
article.story:
RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Dellena Criner and Jessica Preslar each scored
18 points as Nevada rode hot shooting to a 76-61 victory over San
Jose State in the quarterfinals of the Western Athletic Conference
women's tournament.

Fifth-seeded Nevada (13-16) shot 50 percent from the field and
90.9 percent from the free-throw line to beat No. 4 seed San Jose
State (13-15).

The Wolf Pack's 30 free throws made, out of 33 attempts, tied a
tournament record set by Rice last year.

San Jose State was led by forward Amber Jackson's double-double
of 23 points and 13 rebounds.

The Wolf Pack, which lost twice to the Spartans earlier this
season, led 35-27 at halftime. But San Jose State chipped away at
the lead and tied it at 59 on Jackson's lay-up with 5:33 to play.

Nevada answered with an 8-0 run capped by Brandi Fitzgerald's
lay-up with 2:55 to left. After a bucket by Anetero Uiagalelei,
Nevada scored the final nine points of the game with five coming
from the line.

Brandi Fitzgerald scored 11 points for Nevada and Cherlanda
Franklin has 10 points and nine rebounds.

Lamisha Augustine scored 17 points for the Spartans and Alisha
Hicks added 10.
